# Nom — A Compositional-Semantic Programming Language

**Software is language. A .nomtu is a word. A .nom is a sentence. A binary is a story.**

Nom is the programming language that emerges from composing .nomtu words
from an online dictionary into verified applications. It does not replace
existing languages — it consumes them. Every function extracted from
Rust, C, Python, Go, TypeScript, Java, and C++ becomes a .nomtu word.
Programs are compositions of proven meaning, not invented code.

## The Names

**Nom** — the language. Named after Chu Nom (字喃), the Vietnamese writing
system where each character encodes both meaning and sound. Each .nomtu
encodes both semantics (contract) and identity (content hash).

**.nomtu** — the dictionary entry. A word. Each .nomtu describes one concept
with a contract, scores, provenance, and a descriptive sentence for
semantic search. All text. No binary. The implementation is stored
separately in the registry.

**.nom** — the source file. A sentence. Written in English (with foreign
borrowing when English lacks precision). Writing-style syntax: no braces,
no semicolons, no required tabs. Classifiers start declarations.
Blank lines separate them.

**nomdict** — the online dictionary at nom.dev. Indexes millions of .nomtu
entries. Searchable by name, description, contract, and scores.

## The Paradigm: Compositional-Semantic Programming

Nom is not imperative, functional, or object-oriented.
It is the fifth paradigm:

    Imperative   — you tell the machine what to do (C, Go)
    Functional   — you describe transformations (Haskell, ML)
    Object       — you model the world as objects (Java, C#)
    Actor        — you model the world as agents (Erlang)
    Compositional-Semantic — you write sentences, the compiler composes
                             from a dictionary of proven meaning (Nom)

## Writing-Style Syntax

No braces. No semicolons. No required indentation.
English by default. Foreign words when English is imprecise.
Classifiers start declarations. Blank lines end them.

    system auth
    need hash::argon2 where security>0.9
    need store::redis where reliability>0.8
    flow request->hash->store->response
    require latency<50ms

    flow userprofile
    need auth::jwt
    need database::postgres
    flow request->auth->database->response

    test authsecurity
    given auth with mockstore
    when request with token expired
    then response.status = 401

## The Pipeline

    .nom → nom compiler → .nomiz → LLVM → native binary

    No Rust in the middle. No Python. No C. Direct to binary.
    Assembly-smooth performance. Zero runtime overhead.

## The Dictionary

    nom.dev hosts millions of .nomtu entries.
    Each .nomtu is a text file describing one concept.
    The compiler downloads and caches .nomtu on demand.
    nom.lock pins exact selections for reproducible builds.
    Content-addressed: same implementation = same hash = tamper-proof.
